{"ts":"2026-06-27T20:21:47.187Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"tool","toolName":"read_files","toolCallId":"e33iqke4","output":[{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_5_MVP_BACKEND.md","result":"  1 | # GFF AI Platform: Phase 5 Local MVP Backend Setup & Developer Guide\n  2 | \n  3 | This document establishes the strategic, technical, and operational manual for configuring and running the **Phase 5 Local MVP Backend** of the GFF AI Platform. \n  4 | \n  5 | To support the premium, high-fidelity presentation layer developed in Phase 4, Phase 5 introduces a lightweight, high-performance local FastAPI backend. This local server connects to a local SQLite database, processes authentications via JSON Web Tokens (JWT), and hosts multi-tenant workspaces so that developers and stakeholders can test complete client and administrative flows locally.\n  6 | \n  7 | ---\n  8 | \n  9 | ## 1. Executive Narrative & Architectural Scope\n 10 | \n 11 | ### 1.1. Decoupled Sandbox Metaphor\n 12 | In alignment with the GFF AI **Sovereign Operating System** philosophy, the Phase 5 backend is engineered as a local developer sandbox. It replicates multi-tenant access control and core database persistence without introducing complex, expensive production dependencies. \n 13 | \n 14 | This local engine acts as the \"State Synchronizer\" for the frontend cockpit, enabling real-time REST API handshakes, dynamic database logging, and role-based clearance verification.\n 15 | \n 16 | ### 1.2. Scope & Boundaries (MVP Development Phase)\n 17 | The Phase 5 backend is designed **exclusively for local development, demonstration, and offline evaluation**. It provides a solid architectural foundation while intentionally omitting several enterprise cloud-scale features.\n 18 | \n 19 | > ⚠️ **Phase Scope Limitations**:\n 20 | > *   **Local-Only Database**: Uses a local SQLite file (`dev.db`). No RDS/Postgres database setups are used.\n 21 | > *   **No AWS Integrations**: Does not utilize real AWS resources (such as DynamoDB, S3 file buckets, or AWS IAM roles).\n 22 | > *   **No Storage Backend**: File uploads and secure legal document storage are handled via frontend-only simulation placeholders; no physical file-saving backend is active.\n 23 | > *   **No External Payment Gateways**: Computational \"Epoch\" invoicing and billing tables exist in SQLite, but there is no integration with billing aggregators like Stripe or Chargebee.\n 24 | > *   **No Real Emails/OTP/SSO**: There is no live SMTP mailer, Multi-Factor/One-Time Password (OTP) verification, or OAuth2/SSO identity providers. Auth relies strictly on standard OAuth2 JWT tokens with local bcrypt hashing.\n 25 | > *   **No Live Backend for GFF AI Tools**: Tool execution engines, prompt generators, and agent configurations run within mock sandboxes inside the frontend client.\n 26 | > *   **No Production Auth Hardening**: Features like Rate-limiting, IP-restrictions, secure HttpOnly cookie session management, or Hardware Security Module (HSM) signing are deferred to production deployment phases.\n 27 | \n 28 | ---\n 29 | \n 30 | ## 2. Prerequisites\n 31 | \n 32 | Ensure you have the following environments installed locally on your system:\n 33 | *   **Node.js**: `v18.x` or later (for running the Next.js frontend)\n 34 | *   **Python**: `v3.12.x` or later (for running the FastAPI backend)\n 35 | *   **pip**: Python package manager\n 36 | *   **SQLite3**: Installed on your system (typically comes bundled with Python)\n 37 | \n 38 | ---\n 39 | \n 40 | ## 3. Local Environment Variables Configuration\n 41 | \n 42 | To bridge the Next.js frontend and the FastAPI backend, you must establish environment templates in both repositories.\n 43 | \n 44 | ### 3.1. Create Backend Environment\n 45 | Copy the backend configuration template inside the `backend` folder:\n 46 | ```bash\n 47 | cp backend/.env.example backend/.env\n 48 | ```\n 49 | \n 50 | Your `backend/.env` file will look like this:\n 51 | ```env\n 52 | # GFF AI Local MVP Backend Configuration\n 53 | PROJECT_NAME=\"GFF AI Enterprise API\"\n 54 | API_V1_STR=\"/api/v1\"\n 55 | ENVIRONMENT=\"development\"\n 56 | DATABASE_URL=\"sqlite:///dev.db\"\n 57 | \n 58 | # Local JWT configuration\n 59 | JWT_SECRET=\"gff_ai_super_secret_local_key_for_jwt_tokens_2026\"\n 60 | ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES=11520  # 8 Days\n 61 | \n 62 | # Allowed CORS Origins\n 63 | CORS_ORIGINS=\"http://localhost:3000,http://127.0.0.1:3000\"\n 64 | FRONTEND_BASE_URL=\"http://localhost:3000\"\n 65 | ```\n 66 | \n 67 | ### 3.2. Create Frontend Environment\n 68 | Copy the frontend environment template in the project root:\n 69 | ```bash\n 70 | cp .env.example .env\n 71 | ```\n 72 | \n 73 | To enable active backend connectivity in the Next.js frontend, configure `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` in the root `.env` to point to the local FastAPI port:\n 74 | ```env\n 75 | # API Integration\n 76 | NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000/api/v1\n 77 | NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV=development\n 78 | NEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED=true\n 79 | ```\n 80 | \n 81 | *Note: If `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` is omitted or commented out, the frontend gracefully falls back to its client-side mock handlers.*\n 82 | \n 83 | ---\n 84 | \n 85 | ## 4. Local Backend Setup & Installation\n 86 | \n 87 | To streamline development, root-level convenience scripts are provided in the master `package.json` file. These scripts manage virtual environments and package installations automatically.\n 88 | \n 89 | ### 4.1. Automatic Automated Installation (Recommended)\n 90 | From the **root directory** of the project, run:\n 91 | ```bash\n 92 | npm run backend:install\n 93 | ```\n 94 | This automated command:\n 95 | 1.  Enters the `backend/` directory.\n 96 | 2.  Creates a Python virtual environment (`venv/`) if it does not exist.\n 97 | 3.  Upgrades pip and installs all required dependencies from `backend/requirements.txt`.\n 98 | 4.  Generates a `.env` file from `.env.example` if it is missing.\n 99 | \n100 | ### 4.2. Manual Installation\n101 | If you prefer setting up the workspace manually, execute the following commands in your terminal:\n102 | ```bash\n103 | # Navigate to the backend directory\n104 | cd backend\n105 | \n106 | # Create virtual environment\n107 | python3 -m venv venv\n108 | \n109 | # Activate virtual environment\n110 | # On macOS / Linux:\n111 | source venv/bin/activate\n112 | # On Windows (CMD):\n113 | # venv\\Scripts\\activate.bat\n114 | \n115 | # Install package dependencies\n116 | pip install -r requirements.txt\n117 | ```\n118 | \n119 | ---\n120 | \n121 | ## 5. Database Initialization & Seeding\n122 | \n123 | The backend utilizes SQLite for multi-tenant data storage. The database tables are automatically initialized during FastAPI startup, but you must seed the tables to bootstrap enterprise development users and sample data.\n124 | \n125 | ### 5.1. Initialize & Seed Database\n126 | From the **root directory**, run:\n127 | ```bash\n128 | npm run backend:seed\n129 | ```\n130 | Alternatively, from the `backend` folder with your virtual environment active:\n131 | ```bash\n132 | python app/seed.py\n133 | ```\n134 | \n135 | This bootstraps a local SQLite file named `dev.db` inside the `backend/` directory and populates it with:\n136 | *   **Multi-tenant Client Accounts**: Apex Global, Chevron Corporation, and other reference enterprise enclaves.\n137 | *   **Projects & Sandboxes**: Dynamic multi-agent project pipelines mapped to roles and clients.\n138 | *   **Governance Audits**: Simulated compliance frameworks, compliance standards, and compliance tracking items.\n139 | *   **Secure Documents**: Legal records, service-level contracts, and ISO checklists.\n140 | *   **Billing Ledger & Invoices**: Compute epochs, consumption hours, and signed developer invoices.\n141 | *   **System Logs**: Dynamic audit logging structures.\n142 | \n143 | ### 5.2. Database Seeder Idempotency & Reset\n144 | *   **Idempotency**: Running `npm run backend:seed` repeatedly is fully idempotent. It verifies existing primary records before inserting, preventing duplicated keys or rows.\n145 | *   **Wiping the slate clean**: To hard reset the database (drop all tables, recreate schemas, and fresh seed), run the seeder script with the `--reset` flag:\n146 |     ```bash\n147 |     cd backend\n148 |     venv/bin/python app/seed.py --reset\n149 |     ```\n150 | \n151 | ---\n152 | \n153 | ## 6. Running the Services\n154 | \n155 | To test the end-to-end integration, you must run both the backend FastAPI server and the Next.js frontend simultaneously.\n156 | \n157 | ### 6.1. Launching the Backend (FastAPI)\n158 | From the **root directory**, run:\n159 | ```bash\n160 | npm run backend:dev\n161 | ```\n162 | This starts the Uvicorn ASGI server on `http://localhost:8000` with hot-reloading active.\n163 | \n164 | #### Active Ports & URLs:\n165 | *   **Service Root**: [http://localhost:8000](http://localhost:8000) (Automatically redirects to `/docs`)\n166 | *   **Interactive Swagger UI**: [http://localhost:8000/docs](http://localhost:8000/docs) (OpenAPI spec explorer)\n167 | *   **Dynamic Health Check**: [http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health](http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health)\n168 | \n169 | ### 6.2. Launching the Frontend (Next.js)\n170 | In a separate terminal window, from the **root directory**, run:\n171 | ```bash\n172 | npm run dev\n173 | ```\n174 | This starts the Next.js web application on [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000).\n175 | \n176 | \n177 | ---\n178 | \n179 | ## 7. Authenticating and Testing Portal/Admin Flows\n180 | \n181 | ### 7.1. Pre-Configured Developer Accounts & Roles\n182 | The seeder bootstraps five distinct users across different enterprise roles. You can log in using these credentials to test role-based access control (RBAC):\n183 | \n184 | | User Email | Assigned Role | Tenant Affiliation | Clear Password | Intended Test Flow |\n185 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n186 | | **gff_admin@gff.ai** | `gff_admin` | Platform Global | `password123` | Full administrative oversight, Client registry management, Audit logs, System-wide statistics. |\n187 | | **client_admin@apex.com** | `client_admin` | Apex Global | `password123` | Apex Client admin dashboard, Project pipelines, Billing summaries, Document review, Support. |\n188 | | **client_member@apex.com** | `client_member` | Apex Global | `password123` | Standard client operative view, Read-only billing, Read-write support tickets & compliance audits. |\n189 | | **admin@gff.ai** | `admin` | Platform Global | `gff_enterprise_admin_pass_2026` | Legacy administrative fallback authentication flow. |\n190 | | **client@chevron.com** | `client` | Chevron Corp | `chevron_secure_pass_2026` | Legacy single-tenant client dashboard authentication flow. |\n191 | \n192 | ### 7.2. Handshake Verification (End-to-End Test)\n193 | 1.  Open [http://localhost:3000/portal/login](http://localhost:3000/portal/login) (or `/admin/login`).\n194 | 2.  Observe the **Living Terminal Feed** on the right side. It will report:\n195 |     `[SYS] API backend service connection verified. Active mode: REST API.`\n196 | 3.  Enter credentials (e.g., `client_admin@apex.com` and `password123`).\n197 | 4.  Click **Initiate Secure Access**.\n198 | 5.  The system performs a cryptographic handshake, calling `/api/v1/auth/login` on the FastAPI server to retrieve a JWT, saves it in `localStorage` as `gff_api_token`, and routes you to the secure Client Dashboard (`/portal/dashboard`).\n199 | 6.  The backend validates the JWT token on every subsequent API call and scopes database queries based on the tenant (e.g., users logged in under Apex Global will not see Chevron Corporation's private projects).\n200 | \n201 | ---\n202 | \n203 | ## 8. Developer Troubleshooting Guide\n204 | \n205 | ### 8.1. Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) Issues\n206 | *   **Symptom**: The console shows `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` errors, or login handshakes fail with network/CORS block messages.\n207 | *   **Resolution**: \n208 |     1. Check your `backend/.env` file. Ensure `CORS_ORIGINS` is configured with the exact URL of your running frontend (usually `http://localhost:3000`).\n209 |     2. Multiple origins should be separated by commas without spaces, or formatted as a JSON list (e.g., `[\"http://localhost:3000\",\"http://127.0.0.1:3000\"]`).\n210 |     3. Restart your FastAPI backend server after updating `.env`.\n211 | \n212 | ### 8.2. Missing Database / SQLite Locks\n213 | *   **Symptom**: SQLite database errors like `OperationalError: no such table` or `database is locked` appear in the backend terminal logs.\n214 | *   **Resolution**:\n215 |     1. Verify that `dev.db` has been successfully created in the `backend/` directory.\n216 |     2. Run `npm run backend:seed` to initialize the SQLite database schema and seed user models.\n217 |     3. If SQLite reports a database lock, ensure there are no active, hanging Python processes or DB browsers holding a transaction open. Kill any zombie python processes:\n218 |        - macOS/Linux: `killall python python3` or `pkill uvicorn`\n219 |        - Windows: `taskkill /F /IM python.exe`\n220 | \n221 | ### 8.3. Invalid or Expired JWT Token\n222 | *   **Symptom**: Frontend queries immediately redirect back to login routes, or return `401 Unauthorized` responses in the developer console.\n223 | *   **Resolution**:\n224 |     1. Ensure the `JWT_SECRET` configured in your `backend/.env` matches what the backend loads. If the secret changed during server restarts, old tokens stored in your browser will become invalid.\n225 |     2. Clear your browser storage. Open the DevTools console and execute:\n226 |        ```javascript\n227 |        localStorage.clear();\n228 |        ```\n229 |     3. Re-authenticate via `/portal/login` to establish a fresh JWT token handshake.\n230 | \n231 | ### 8.4. Seed Rerun Failures\n232 | *   **Symptom**: Running the seeder yields unique constraint violations or integrity errors.\n233 | *   **Resolution**:\n234 |     1. The seeder is designed to be idempotent and update fields when keys match. However, if structural schema alterations were made to the SQLAlchemy models, migrations may conflict.\n235 |     2. Wipe the tables and run a clean bootstrap using the reset argument:\n236 |        ```bash\n237 |        npm run backend:seed -- --reset\n238 |        ```\n239 |        *(Note: The extra `--` passes the `--reset` option through npm to the python seed runner script).*\n240 | ","success":true},{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_5_SECURITY_LIMITATIONS.md","result":"  1 | # GFF AI Platform: Phase 5 Security Limitations & Phase 6 Hardening Roadmap\n  2 | \n  3 | This document serves as the official **Enterprise Security Audit and Risk Assessment** for **Phase 5** of the GFF AI Platform. It provides a transparent, honest, and rigorous evaluation of the current MVP’s security limitations and outlines the explicit architectural requirements for **Phase 6 Enterprise Security Hardening**.\n  4 | \n  5 | ---\n  6 | \n  7 | ## 1. Security Philosophy & The Local Sandbox Metaphor\n  8 | \n  9 | In alignment with the GFF AI **Sovereign Operating System** architecture, the Phase 5 release is designed exclusively as a **local developer sandbox, high-fidelity presentation prototype, and demonstration environment**. \n 10 | \n 11 | To optimize developer ergonomics, reduce evaluation friction, and enable offline-first demonstrations, certain enterprise-grade security protocols have been deferred or simplified. While the user interface models perfect-fidelity access patterns, MFA dialogs, and compliance logs, the underlying execution engine runs within a defined **Local Boundary**.\n 12 | \n 13 | ```\n 14 | +-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 15 | |                              PHASE 5 SECURITY BOUNDARY                            |\n 16 | |                                                                                   |\n 17 | |  [ NEXT.JS FRONTEND ] <=========( Local Loopback HTTP )==========> [ FASTAPI MVP ]  |\n 18 | |          |                                                              |         |\n 19 | |   (localStorage)                                                    (dev.db)      |\n 20 | |          |                                                              |         |\n 21 | |     JWT Session                                                      SQLite3      |\n 22 | |                                                                                   |\n 23 | |  * Strictly isolated to localhost.                                                 |\n 24 | |  * Intended only for local demonstration, offline audits, and validation.         |\n 25 | +-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 26 | ```\n 27 | \n 28 | This document establishes a clear separation between the **Phase 5 Sandbox** and the **Phase 6 Production Target** to ensure that compliance officers, CISOs, and enterprise architects can safely plan their sovereign deployments.\n 29 | \n 30 | ---\n 31 | \n 32 | ## 2. Phase 5 MVP Security Limitations (An Honest Evaluation)\n 33 | \n 34 | Below is an exhaustive matrix of the technical security limitations present in the Phase 5 local MVP backend. These compromises are typical for local evaluation and rapid prototyping phases, but must be mitigated before any public or production hosting.\n 35 | \n 36 | ### 2.1. Client-Side Authentication Token Storage (JWT)\n 37 | *   **Current State**: Access tokens generated by the FastAPI backend are stored in the client's web browser using `localStorage` or development-only memory states.\n 38 | *   **Security Implication**: Storage via `localStorage` is vulnerable to **Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)** attacks. If a malicious script is executed in the user's browser context (e.g., via a compromised third-party package dependency), the token can be read directly by client-side JavaScript.\n 39 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Acceptable only because the sandbox is run in isolated local host environments (`localhost:3000`) where external script injections are highly controlled.\n 40 | \n 41 | ### 2.2. Persistence Engine (Local SQLite DB)\n 42 | *   **Current State**: Data is stored inside a single local SQLite file (`dev.db`) within the backend directory.\n 43 | *   **Security Implication**: SQLite does not support robust concurrent user lock patterns, lacks granular row-level security policies (RLS), does not natively encrypt records at rest without specialized extensions (such as SQLCipher), and lacks high-availability (HA) database clustering.\n 44 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Ideal for zero-dependency local setups (runs immediately without Docker or external DB servers) but vulnerable to data loss or file corruption in production high-load environments.\n 45 | \n 46 | ### 2.3. Identity Bootstrapping (Local Seed Users)\n 47 | *   **Current State**: System administrative and client-tenant credentials are bootstrapped via a local seeder file (`app/seed.py`) with pre-configured developer passwords hashed using standard bcrypt algorithms.\n 48 | *   **Security Implication**: Shared seed credentials and static administrative initial states exist inside public Git repositories for local evaluation. Leaving these unchanged exposes systems to instant compromise.\n 49 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Local developer accounts are strictly for offline demonstration and testing.\n 50 | \n 51 | ### 2.4. Lack of Production Password Reset Loops\n 52 | *   **Current State**: There is no live SMTP or transactional email delivery service integrated. Triggering a password reset process only simulates a cryptographic operation on the client interface without delivering a verified token.\n 53 | *   **Security Implication**: Users cannot recover lost credentials securely. Any reset attempt lacks server-side verification loops, token expiration tracking, or IP-based rate protection.\n 54 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: The system relies on manually updating or resetting the SQLite user table locally.\n 55 | \n 56 | ### 2.5. Simulated Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)\n 57 | *   **Current State**: The Multi-Factor Authentication / One-Time Password (MFA/OTP) screen simulates state-of-the-art cryptographic sequence rotations and streams live diagnostic eBPF logs. However, it does not perform server-side verification of TOTP algorithms.\n 58 | *   **Security Implication**: The security benefit of 2FA/MFA is bypassed at the API level during the MVP phase.\n 59 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Implemented purely for visual and user-experience validation to show clients how premium security overrides will function in the final product.\n 60 | \n 61 | ### 2.6. Absence of Refresh Token Hardening & Rotation\n 62 | *   **Current State**: The system utilizes a single-tier JWT access token with a long expiration duration (8 days/11520 minutes configured in `.env` for developer convenience). There are no secure refresh tokens, rotation mechanisms, or active blacklists.\n 63 | *   **Security Implication**: If a session JWT is intercepted or leaked, the attacker gains unrestricted access for the entire lifecycle of the token (8 days) with no server-side capability to revoke individual active sessions.\n 64 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Maximizes convenience for developers testing flows without constant re-authentication.\n 65 | \n 66 | ### 2.7. Session Transport Strategy (No httpOnly Cookies)\n 67 | *   **Current State**: Secure session transport has not been enforced. JWTs are passed directly via authorization headers from the browser's storage rather than transmitted via secure, browser-managed cookies.\n 68 | *   **Security Implication**: Standard browser header injection does not benefit from native web-browser protections against cross-site leakage or session hijacking.\n 69 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Standard local REST API implementation pattern.\n 70 | \n 71 | ### 2.8. Lack of Perimeter Protection & Rate Limiting\n 72 | *   **Current State**: The FastAPI MVP has no middleware limits on requests per second, IP restriction gates, or brute-force dictionary attack protections.\n 73 | *   **Security Implication**: Malicious actors could easily execute denial-of-service (DDoS) requests or run rapid credential stuffing attacks against the `/token` endpoint to compromise seed accounts.\n 74 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Relying strictly on local developer isolation to protect API endpoints.\n 75 | \n 76 | ### 2.9. Audit-Grade Logging & Log Immutability\n 77 | *   **Current State**: System activity, model runs, and administration operations are written to standard terminal standard outputs (Stdout) and basic local SQLite audit tables.\n 78 | *   **Security Implication**: Local logs are mutable (can be easily deleted or edited by any user with access to the `dev.db` file) and do not support structured JSON telemetry required by modern SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) collectors.\n 79 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Logs are designed for immediate developer diagnostics, not compliance forensic auditing.\n 80 | \n 81 | ### 2.10. Non-Hardened Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)\n 82 | *   **Current State**: Basic role routing and decorator security checks ensure standard frontend navigation safety. However, a comprehensive, formal security audit of RBAC execution layers and API endpoints has not been performed.\n 83 | *   **Security Implication**: Potential exists for \"broken object-level authorization\" (BOLA) or privilege escalation if endpoints are accessed directly via raw API requests with manipulated tenant IDs.\n 84 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Focused on simulating the visual states of 7 core roles.\n 85 | \n 86 | ### 2.11. Absence of File Scanning & Malware Filtering\n 87 | *   **Current State**: The portal's secure legal vault and document indexing systems simulate sovereign compliance. When files are uploaded in the sandbox, they bypass physical antivirus or malware scanners.\n 88 | *   **Security Implication**: Uploading infected PDF/Word documents could expose admin users or automated parse agents to security vulnerabilities when files are fetched or processed.\n 89 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Completely offline-safe since uploaded assets are only mocked in browser-side execution contexts.\n 90 | \n 91 | ### 2.12. Zero Payment Compliance Integration\n 92 | *   **Current State**: Dynamic billing ledgers, SLA logs, and consumption invoices are calculated dynamically via database seeds. No actual integrations exist with payment providers (such as Stripe) or PCI-DSS auditing structures.\n 93 | *   **Security Implication**: The billing system is not designed to hold live banking, credit card, or payment routing keys, and does not comply with international financial security standards.\n 94 | *   **Phase 5 Boundary**: Intended strictly for operational and compute cost simulation.\n 95 | \n 96 | \n 97 | ---\n 98 | \n 99 | ## 3. Phase 6 Enterprise Security Hardening Roadmap\n100 | \n101 | To prepare the GFF AI Platform for enterprise deployment and strict compliance certifications (such as SOC 2 Type II, ISO/IEC 27001:2022, and GDPR/HIPAA enclaves), the following hardening roadmap is established. \n102 | \n103 | ```\n104 | +----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n105 | |                                    PHASE 6 HARDENED PRODUCTION TARGET                                    |\n106 | |                                                                                                          |\n107 | |  [ SECURE CLIENTS ] =====( TLS 1.3 / strict HSTS )=====> [ AWS WAF / Perimeter Gate ]                    |\n108 | |                                                                 |                                        |\n109 | |                                                     [ SECURE REVERSE PROXY / CORS ]                      |\n110 | |                                                                 |                                        |\n111 | |  [ FRONTEND ENGINE ] ===( httpOnly / Secure Cookie )===> [ FASTAPI CLUSTERED APPS ]                     |\n112 | |                                                                 |                                        |\n113 | |                                                       ( AWS KMS AES-256 Encryption )                     |\n114 | |                                                       ( AWS Secrets Manager, IAM Roles )                 |\n115 | |                                                                 |                                        |\n116 | |                                                      [ RDS POSTGRESQL MULTI-AZ ]                         |\n117 | +----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n118 | ```\n119 | \n120 | ### 3.1. Production-Grade Persistence Engine\n121 | *   **Action Plan**: Migrate the database storage engine from a local SQLite file to a managed, high-availability PostgreSQL cluster (e.g., **AWS Aurora Serverless v2** or **Azure Database for PostgreSQL**).\n122 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n123 |     *   Deploy the database cluster exclusively inside **Private Subnets** within an enterprise Virtual Private Cloud (VPC), blocking direct public internet access.\n124 |     *   Enforce **Encryption-at-Rest** using AWS KMS (AES-256) keys.\n125 |     *   Enable SSL/TLS certificates for all SQL connections.\n126 |     *   Utilize PostgreSQL **Row-Level Security (RLS)** to enforce absolute multi-tenant data segregation.\n127 | \n128 | ### 3.2. Hardened Cookie-Based Session Storage\n129 | *   **Action Plan**: Transition from `localStorage` token storage to a server-managed, cookie-based session transport strategy.\n130 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n131 |     *   Store JWTs or Session IDs inside standard HTTP cookies.\n132 |     *   Configure cookie headers with strict defense flags:\n133 |         *   `HttpOnly`: Prevents client-side scripts (JavaScript) from accessing the session token, completely neutralizing XSS-based token theft.\n134 |         *   `Secure`: Forces the browser to transmit cookies exclusively over encrypted HTTPS/TLS connections.\n135 |         *   `SameSite=Strict` or `SameSite=Lax`: Mitigates **Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)** vulnerabilities by restricting cookie transmission on cross-origin requests.\n136 | \n137 | ### 3.3. Refresh Token Rotation (RTR)\n138 | *   **Action Plan**: Implement a dual-token authentication system using a short-lived Access Token (e.g., 15 minutes) and a hardened Refresh Token stored securely in a redis-backed fast session database.\n139 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n140 |     *   **Rotation**: Every time a client requests a new access token using a refresh token, a new refresh token is issued, and the previous token is immediately invalidated.\n141 |     *   **Replay Attack Detection**: If a used or old refresh token is presented, the system flags a high-priority security anomaly, invalidates the entire active session family, and forces immediate re-authentication.\n142 | \n143 | ### 3.4. Enterprise Password Recovery Loop\n144 | *   **Action Plan**: Deploy a fully secured transactional email pipeline utilizing enterprise gateways (e.g., AWS SES, SendGrid, or Mailgun).\n145 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n146 |     *   Generate cryptographically secure, high-entropy, short-lived reset tokens (expiring in 15 minutes).\n147 |     *   Transmit reset links via HTTPS.\n148 |     *   Ensure the password reset API does not disclose user existence (preventing account enumeration attacks).\n149 |     *   Record and log password update events within the audit trail.\n150 | \n151 | ### 3.5. Production Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) & Enterprise SSO\n152 | *   **Action Plan**: Replace the high-fidelity MFA simulations with real server-side cryptographic verification and Enterprise Single Sign-On (SSO) systems.\n153 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n154 |     *   **TOTP Verification**: Implement standard server-side verification using standard algorithms (RFC 6238) compatible with Google Authenticator, Microsoft Authenticator, or Bitwarden.\n155 |     *   **Federated Identity**: Integrate SAML 2.0 / OpenID Connect (OIDC) protocols to support corporate identity providers (such as Okta, Microsoft Entra ID / Active Directory, Ping Identity, and Duo).\n156 | \n157 | \n158 | ### 3.6. Network-Level Traffic Control & Rate Limiting\n159 | *   **Action Plan**: Introduce application-level and network-level perimeter protections.\n160 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n161 |     *   Deploy **FastAPI-Limiter** on all sensitive backend API endpoints (specifically `/token`, login gates, and document ingest points) powered by Redis token-bucket mechanics.\n162 |     *   Position the platform behind global Web Application Firewalls (such as **Cloudflare Enterprise** or **AWS WAF**) to block SQL injections, cross-site scripting payloads, and malicious bot traffic.\n163 |     *   Implement smart IP throttling, rate thresholds, and temporary quarantine zones for suspicious client networks.\n164 | \n165 | ### 3.7. Immutable Audit Logging & SIEM Integration\n166 | *   **Action Plan**: Standardize all logging to write structured, machine-readable JSON payloads containing ISO 8601 timestamps, actor IDs, client tenant contexts, and exact API parameters.\n167 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n168 |     *   Stream log output in real time to external cloud aggregators (e.g., **AWS CloudWatch Logs**, **Datadog**, or **Splunk**).\n169 |     *   Configure log storage with write-once-read-many (WORM) configurations, ensuring logs cannot be modified, deleted, or corrupted, satisfying SOC 2 forensic auditing criteria.\n170 |     *   Establish high-severity alerts for abnormal behaviors (e.g., mass document downloads, administrative role swaps, or unauthorized login attempts).\n171 | \n172 | ### 3.8. Enterprise Secrets Management\n173 | *   **Action Plan**: Completely eliminate environment variable declarations of sensitive credentials inside local files, code repositories, or static server configurations.\n174 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n175 |     *   Integrate the backend with dedicated key vaults such as **AWS Secrets Manager**, **HashiCorp Vault**, or **Azure Key Vault**.\n176 |     *   Enable automatic, scheduled rotation of database credentials, third-party API keys, and JWT cryptographic signing secrets.\n177 |     *   Restrict access to key vaults using fine-grained IAM resource policies.\n178 | \n179 | ### 3.9. Secure Deployment Configuration & IaC Hardening\n180 | *   **Action Plan**: Package the entire system into secure, lightweight Docker containers and orchestrate deployments via **AWS ECS (Fargate)** or Kubernetes (**AWS EKS**).\n181 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n182 |     *   Construct Dockerfiles using slim, non-root base images, ensuring processes do not run with root permissions inside the container.\n183 |     *   Utilize Infrastructure-as-Code (IaC) tools (e.g., **Terraform**) to configure networks, enforcing private subnets, secure security groups, and disabling public IPv4 addresses on execution nodes.\n184 |     *   Mandate **TLS 1.3** across all load balancers with automated HTTPS certificate renewals.\n185 | \n186 | ### 3.10. Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) Hardening\n187 | *   **Action Plan**: Remove any generic or wildcard declarations (`*`) from CORS origins in production configuration files.\n188 | *   **Security Protocols**:\n189 |     *   Establish strict whitelist parameters mapping exclusively to certified, company-owned corporate domains (e.g., `https://portal.gff.ai` and `https://admin.gff.ai`).\n190 |     *   Enforce HTTP header protections, including:\n191 |         *   `Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS)`\n192 |         *   `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`\n193 |         *   `X-Frame-Options: DENY` (to prevent clickjacking)\n194 |         *   `Content-Security-Policy (CSP)` (to explicitly whitelist allowed script domains and disable inline scripts).\n195 | \n196 | ---\n197 | \n198 | ## 4. Compliance Goal Tracking Matrix\n199 | \n200 | The transition from Phase 5 to Phase 6 is engineered to align directly with major global compliance frameworks. The table below highlights how the planned hardening steps fulfill key control requirements.\n201 | \n202 | | Compliance Framework | Target Control | Phase 5 MVP Status | Phase 6 Production Remediation Plan |\n203 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n204 | | **SOC 2 Type II** | CC6.1 - Access Transmission | ⚠️ Partial (Plain headers over HTTP localhost) | Complete (TLS 1.3, HttpOnly/Secure cookies, HSTS) |\n205 | | **SOC 2 Type II** | CC6.3 - Role-Based Access | ⚠️ Basic (Frontend-focused simulated routing) | Complete (Strict endpoint decorators with RLS PostgreSQL) |\n206 | | **ISO 27001:2022** | A.8.20 - Network Security | ❌ No active network rate limits / WAF | Complete (AWS WAF, FastAPI token-bucket limits via Redis) |\n207 | | **ISO 27001:2022** | A.8.12 - Log Auditing | ⚠️ Partial (Mutable local SQLite tables / Stdout) | Complete (Immutable logs streaming to SIEM / CloudWatch) |\n208 | | **HIPAA Security** | 164.312(a)(2)(iv) - Encrypt | ❌ SQLite unencrypted by default | Complete (AWS KMS AES-256 encrypted Aurora storage) |\n209 | | **PCI-DSS 4.0** | Req 8.3 - Secure Passwords | ⚠️ Basic (Standard local bcrypt without complexity) | Complete (Okta SSO, enterprise complexity controls, MFA) |\n210 | \n211 | ---\n212 | \n213 | ## 5. Summary Conclusion\n214 | \n215 | The Phase 5 Local MVP Backend provides a secure, fully functional, and highly visual sandbox to validate GFF AI's sovereign workflows. By isolating execution to `localhost` and explicitly documenting the trade-offs above, we preserve developer productivity while establishing a flawless, production-ready blueprint for Phase 6.\n216 | \n217 | Prior to migrating this codebase to public servers or connecting live customer data, engineering teams **must** execute the hardening steps listed in Section 3 to ensure full operational sovereignty and data security.\n218 | ","success":true}],"durationMs":10}}
